Brief Description:

The Racial and Social Equity Composite Index combines the information of education attainment, English fluency, race (foreign-born or not), health condition that potentially correlated socioeconomic level. The overall percentile with specific weight calculated by the factors above was compared with the actual socioeconomic percentile of the neighborhood to identify where propriety populations make up relatively large proportions of neighborhood residents.

Questions and hypothesis:

First of all, I found this very updated dataset an excellent source for analyzing each factors (race, health condition, English fluency, education attainment) relationship with socioeconomic status and the composite stutus, and the interrelationships of each other. I would like to compare different model to find the relatively the best one to fit. My hypothesis is that the linear regression would not be a reasonable fit for the categorical variable, and I would like to try the non-linear models including poisson and logistic regression models.Additionally, the variables I have chosen have a negative correlation with socialeconomic and composite quantile. Also, there should be a positive correlation between socialeconomic quantile and composite quantile.
Link: https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/racial-and-social-equity-composite-index
Data.gov. (20202021, November 10September 17). Racial and Social Equity Composite Index - CKAN [Dataset]. City of Seattle GIS Program. https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/racial-and-social-equity-composite-index

6 of the variables are chosen with 2 of them as categorical variables.
The categorical variables (socialeconimic quintile and the composite quintile) are the ones that I am trying to connect every these numerical variables with regression models.
The main propose of the project is to build a proper regression model, with different distribution.
My hypothesis here is that to predict a categorical variable, the simple liner regression would not be a perfect fit, and I will use anova test to verify it.

names(df1_cate)[5]<-paste("Socialecon")
df2<-df1_cate%>%
  mutate(Socialecon=if_else(Socialecon=="Highest priority/Most disadvantaged",5,
                   if_else(Socialecon=="Second highest",4,
                           if_else(Socialecon=="Middle",3,
                                   if_else(Socialecon=="Second lowest",2,1)))))
For building a linear relationship with numerical variables and cateorical ones, I firstly index the categorical variables. Giving the five ranks, I index each level with a number from 1 to 5.
names(df2)[6]<-paste("Composite")
df3<-df2%>%
  mutate(Composite=if_else(Composite=="Highest priority/Most disadvantaged",5,
                   if_else(Composite=="Second highest",4,
                           if_else(Composite=="Middle",3,
                                   if_else(Composite=="Second lowest",2,1)))))

Based on ANOVA test of linear regression and poisson non-linear regression. We shall acknowledge that the residual sum of squares decreased from 78.375 to 39.307 from the linear regression model to the poisson regression model in the case of the relationship modeling of Socialeconomic quantile and other variables, and from 65.949 to 35.910 in the case of the relationship modeling of Composite quantile and other variables.
It is enough to prove that linear regression would not be as good as non-linear regression in these cases. The next step is to compare the poisson distribution with the logistic distribution.

Non-linear Regression - Logistic

The rule of thumb in non-linear regression model is to choose the one with the least AIC. Comparing the Poisson distribution regression model and the logistic regression model we can tell both log1(the logistic regression model of between Socialeconomic quantile and other variables) and log2 (the logistic regression model of between Composite quantile and other variables)s AIC is less than the poisson regression model (ps1 and ps2).
The specific number of AIC in socialeconomic quantile with other variables:
Poisson distribution (ps1) :436.29
Logistic distribution(log1): 398.6937
The specific number of AIC in Composite quantile with other variables:
Poisson distribution (ps2) :431.9
Logistic distribution (log2): 390.5893

Conclusion: From the regression models and the tests above, the logistic model is the best fit overall for the regressions of the dataset.

The estimated regression equations:

Socialeconomic percentile = exp^(3.10 * colored people percentage-14.02 * English less than well percentage-15.6* Diabete percentage-59.04*asthma percentage)

Composite percentile = exp^(-0.2193 * colored people percentage-10.2285 * English less than well percentage-25.96* Diabete percentage+5.4785*asthma percentage)

Therefore, the variables above have mostly the negative correlation with socialeconomic status and composite status, which verifies my hypothesis. However, in the regression model of socialeconomic status and other variables, colored people percentage has a positive correlation with the socialeconomic quantile. In the regression model of Composite quantile and other variables, asthma percentage has a positive correlation with the socialeconomic percentile, which contradicts to my hypothesis.
